record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 156,
  "cap": "TIMING_SIDE_CHANNEL",
  "endpoint": "auth_layer (every /api/v1/* request)",
  "rationale": "constant_eq returns early on a.len() != b.len() (router.rs:156-158) before the XOR loop runs, leaking the configured bearer token length to a remote attacker via 401-response latency. The byte loop below is constant-time, but the length oracle alone reduces brute-force from O(64^N) over all reasonable N to a single fixed N. Combined with the URL-query auth surface (router.rs:142) which leaks the live token to logs, this is one more confirmation channel for an offline cracker who has captured ciphertext or partial leakage. Use subtle::ConstantTimeEq, or pad provided and expected to a fixed buffer before XORing, so length itself is not observable. Static pass missed because the function is *named* constant_eq and the byte loop is correct — the bug is the structural early-return, not a missing operator.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "from a non-loopback origin, send Authorization: Bearer <N random hex chars> for N in 16..96; measure 401 response time distribution; the dip at the true N is the bearer length."
}

